>>32267162
Counterpoint to Strong's advice is that sometimes a conversation or scene starts too early and ends too late.
I've used scenes that are barely a few hundred words because that's all that was needed. Others are 5-7k words.

Is the scene slow or fast? Does it need a ton of exposition and description, or is it (to think of things visually) a series of closeups cut quickly. Eventually you'll build a routine.
I build my stories through dialogue. If you're starting with description, where's the conflict? What motivates the two characters in the scene, and where's the difference? Don't just write something like
>they accepted each other for who they were
>the end

Don't fluff for fluff's sake. Who, what, when, where, why, how?

Anonymous Fri 21 Aug 2020 11:54:57 No.32271893 Report
Quoted By:
>>32266850
Disclaimer: autism. Mileage may vary.

I usually just write and see what happens. I have an outline, both of the story as a whole and of individual chapters/sections, but it's not in any way detailed. If I feel I need something more stable to write around I tend to summarize the point of the scene (What do I want said? What is the character struggling with? Where is the story going next? Does this character need time to digest something that just happened?) before/as I write it. It can help me avoid meandering.

If something feels to short or, indeed, too long, I just wait until I go back and read it later for a revision. Fixing it immediately isn't always helpful. Things might flow in the moment only to feel stilted later, but the opposite is also true. Also, when the whole section is done there are a lot more framing to hang the meat on, which tends to help a lot when working out the flow of individual paragraphs.

I wouldn't worry about fluffing anything, as it all comes down to how you (or your characters) perceive the moment. Sometimes you want long, winding descriptions because the scene deals with digesting something new. Sometimes you want short, quick mentions because there's need for urgency and stopping to smell the flowers would make no sense. Worry less about it being "proper" or following some set rules, and think instead in terms of what you'd do in similar situations. Would you stay and survey? Would you stay and fight, only concerning yourself with that which matters for staying alive? Would you run; ignoring everything that isn't the way forward? That matters a lot more than hitting a specific word count
